model1 = smf.ols("LungCap ~ Height", data=data).fit()
model2 = smf.ols("LungCap ~ Height + np.power(Height,2)", data=data).fit()
model3 = smf.ols("LungCap ~ Height + np.power(Height,2) + np.power(Height,3)", data=data).fit()

In [ ]:
## Height**2 and Height**3 is based on Height so the variance is similar among 3 models. 
## Model 2 is improvement over model 1 because the df residual od model 2 is 651 than model 1 which is 652. 
## Also, the sum sq of model 1 is decreased to 998 and model 1 sum sq is 1088. 
## Model 3 is a slight to no improvement over model 2. The df residual of model 3 is 650 than model 2 which is 651. 
## Also, the sum sq of both the models is 998 and 997.79.
## Through visualization, we can see there is an improvement of model 2 over model 1 if we look at the residual plot. 
## The higher the F-value, the lower the corresponding p-value. 
## In the above plots we can we similar F-value of model 2 and 3 and less P-value.
## Above we have plotted visualization of descriptive analysis, residual and normal QQ, and analysed the p-value and f-value.

## Conclusion:
## The results of ANOVA shows there is a slight improvement of model 2 over model 1, but no improvement between models 2 and 3.
